@NODE MENU_DESCRIPTION
@TITLE "Menu Description"

   When the @{"Main Window" link MAIN_WINDOW} is selected you can access FBase's
   Menu strip. The Following menus are available:

      Project Menu
        @{" New    " link DO_NEW}        Clear all database      (Amiga-N).
        @{" Open   " link DO_OPEN}        Open saved database     (Amiga-O).
        @{" Save   " link DO_SAVE}        Save current database   (Amiga-S).
        @{" SaveAs " link DO_SAVEAS}        Save database under new name.
        @{" Print  " link DO_PRINT}        Print database.
        @{" About  " link DO_ABOUT}        Display info about program.
        @{" Quit   " link DO_QUIT}        Quit FBase              (Amiga-Q).
      Action Menu
        @{" Read   " link DO_READ}        Read a Floppy           (Amiga-R).
        @{" View   " link DO_VIEW}        View Floppy contents    (Amiga-V).
        @{" Edit   " link DO_EDIT}        Edit Floppy contents    (Amiga-E).
        @{" Kill   " link DO_KILL}        Erase contents of a Floppy.
        @{" Find   " link DO_FIND}        Search database         (Amiga-F).
        @{" Keys   " link DO_KEYS}        Define global keys      (Amiga-Y).


   When the @{"Contents Window" link FLOPPY_CONTENTS} is selected the following menus
   are avaiable:

      Action Menu
        @{" Delete " link DO_DELETE}        Delete a Record         (Amiga-D).
        @{" Rename " link DO_RENAME}        Rename a Record         (Amiga-R).
        @{" Remark " link DO_REMARK}        Edit Record Remark      (Amiga-M).
        @{" Keys   " link DO_RKEYS}        Edit Record Keys        (Amiga-K).


   The Following Windows have a Print option under the Project Menu:

     · Floppy Contents Window.
     · View Window.
     · File Info Window.
     · Find List Window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE WINDOW_DESCRIPTION
@TITLE "Window Description"

   FBase displays several windows. To learn more about these windows
   choose one of the following:

        @{" Main Window            " link MAIN_WINDOW}     Floppy List and major actions.
        @{" Floppy Contents Window " link FLOPPY_CONTENTS}     Edit Floppy contents.
        @{" View Window            " link VIEW_WINDOW}     View Floppy contents.
        @{" File Info Window       " link FINFO_WINDOW}     View Record info in full.
        @{" Find Window            " link SEARCH_WINDOW}     Enter search pattern.
        @{" Find List Window       " link FIND_LIST}     View files matching search pattern.
        @{" Keys Window            " link KEYS_WINDOW}     Define the global Keys.
        @{" Record Keys Window     " link RKEYS_WINDOW}     Set Record Keys.
        @{" Search Keys Window     " link SKEYS_WINDOW}     Set Search Keys.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAIN_WINDOW
@TITLE "Main Window"

   The main window is made of three major components:

    · Floppy List    - This list displays the floppies held in the database.
                       To select a Floppy click on it and its name will be
                       displayed at the bottom of the list.
                       When double clicking on a name the @{"View window" link VIEW_WINDOW}
                       will open.

    · Action gadgets - The following actions are avaiable:

                @{" Read   " link DO_READ}      Read a Floppy                   (Key R).
                @{" View   " link DO_VIEW}      View Floppy contents            (Key V).
                @{" Edit   " link DO_EDIT}      Edit Floppy contents            (Key E).
                @{" Kill   " link DO_KILL}      Erase contents of a Floppy.     (Key K).
                @{" Find   " link DO_FIND}      Search database                 (Key F).
                @{" Keys   " link DO_KEYS}      Modify glboal keys.             (Key Y).

    · Floppy select  - Use this gadget to select the Floppy Disk you wish
                       to read from (non Floppy volumes are available also).

   Also this is the window to which FBase's menu is attached.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FLOPPY_CONTENTS
@TITLE "Floppy Contents Window"

   This window displays the contents of a specific Floppy.
   You get here by selecting a floppy from the list and pressing the Edit
   button.

   The following gadgets are available for editing purposes:

        @{" Delete " link DO_DELETE}    Delete a Record         (KEY D).
        @{" Rename " link DO_RENAME}    Rename a Record         (KEY R).
        @{" Remark " link DO_REMARK}    Add a Record Remark     (KEY M).
        @{" Keys   " link DO_RKEYS}    Change Record Keys      (KEY K).

         OK             Accept changes to data.
         CANCEL         Discard changes to data.

   The contents of this window can be printed with a menu command.

@ENDNODE

@NODE VIEW_WINDOW
@TITLE "View Window"

   This window displays the contents of the selected Floppy.
   No editing is available.

   Double clicking on any entry opens the @{"File Info" link FINFO_WINDOW} window for
   that Record.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FINFO_WINDOW
@TITLE "File Info Window"

   This window provides detailed description for the Record you double selected.
   This info includes full path, size, Record remark and all associated keys.

   Use the menu to print the information on this window.

   To exit close this window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SEARCH_WINDOW
@TITLE "Find Window"

   In this window you enter the pattern used to search for Records in your
   database.

   The window contains the following elements:

    · Search String     - Enter the search patter here.
                          @{"WILDCARDS" link WILDCARDS} amiga style are allowed.

    · Ignore Case       - Select whether to ignore pattern case (KEY C).

    · Inc Directories   - Select if Dirs shuld be considered    (KEY D).

    · Set Keys          - Opens the @{"Search Keys" link SKEYS_WINDOW} window          (KEY S).

    · Match Keys        - Determine if Keys are used for search (KEY K).

    · And Keys          - When set ALL Keys must match the      (KEY A).
                          Record Keys. Otherwise at least one Key
                          must match the record keys.

    · OK gadget         - Perform search.

    · CANCEL gadget     - Do not perform search.

   If no matching records are found a message will apear.
   If some records do match the pattern ( and keys) you will be presented with
   the @{"Find List Window" link FIND_LIST}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FIND_LIST
@TITLE "Find List Window"

   After you performed a successful search on your database the results
   are displayed in a list in this window.
   The list displays the complete path to every directory/file.

   Double clicking on any entry open the @{"File Info Window" link FINFO_WINDOW} for
   that Record.

   Use the menu to print the contents of this window.

   To exit this window close it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE KEYS_WINDOW
@TITLE "Keys Window"

   This window lists the available global @{"Keys" link KEYS}.

   It contains the following buttons:

    · Add - Adds a new key to the list.

    · Del - removes the selected key from the list. (NOTE! when deleting a key
                it will be deleted from all Records associated with it.)

   To rename a key select it and enter the new name.

   To leave this window close it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE RKEYS_WINDOW
@TITLE "Record Keys Window"

   In this window you set the @{"Keys" link KEYS} for the selected Record.

   The left list is the source list containing all available keys.
   The right list holds the keys assigned to this Record.
   Mark one (or more) keys from one of the lists & use the arrows to move them.

   Selecting OK changes the Keys for the Record. CANCEL aborts the operation.

   If you are editing a root or directry Record , upon confirming your changes
   you will be asked if you want these changes to be propagated below. Select
   Change to effect only the changes you made (ie. Keys you added or deleted
   will be added or deleted in the sub-files as well). Select Copy to make all
   subfiles have the SAME keys as the header. Select No to change header only.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SKEYS_WINDOW
@TITLE "Search Keys Window"

   In this window you set the @{"Keys" link KEYS} you wish to search on.

   The left list is the source list containing all available keys.
   The right list holds the keys you will search on.
   Mark one (or more) keys from one of the lists & use the arrows to move them.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_NEW
@TITLE "New"

   Use the New command to clear all data held in database.

   You will be asked to confirm this action as it is irreversible.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_OPEN
@TITLE "Open File"

   Use this command to read a previously saved database.

   When you invoke this command a standard Amiga file requester apears ,
   where you can choose the file name.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_SAVE
@TITLE "Save File"

   Use this command to save your database for future use.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_SAVEAS
@TITLE "Save File As"

   Use this command to save your database for future use , giving
   it a new name.

   Amiga standard file requester is provided for selecting a file name.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_PRINT
@TITLE "Print"

   Use this command to print your database or part of it.

   Print All prints all Records in all Floppies.        (Amiga-P).
   Print Titles prints just the Floppiy names.          (Amiga-T).

   Most other informative windows contain a Print option in their menu as well.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_ABOUT
@TITLE "About"

   This command brings up a requester giving some info about the program.
   Mostly Harmless.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_QUIT
@TITLE "Quit"

   You can quit FBase either by selecting the Quit menu option or by
   closing the @{"Main Window" link MAIN_WINDOW}.

   You'll be asked to confirm the action to avoid losing data.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_READ
@TITLE "Read Floppy"

   This command scans the Floppy in the indicated drive ( as chosen in
   the drive select gadget ).

   If the name of the Floppy matches a name already on the list , it is assumed
   that you wish to update that Floppy. A special requester allows you to
   choose the type of update you wish to carry out:

   · by Path - The old Floppy is scanned for Records with identical path names.
               Data from these Records is copied.
   · by Name - Records are matched by name and not full path. Use this option
               If you move a Record around (e.g to a different directory).
   · New     - No data is copied from the old Floppy.
   · No      - You do not wish to update that Floppy. Aborts operation.

   After the disk has been scanned the @{"Floppy Contents window" link FLOPPY_CONTENTS}
   will apear so you can edit the data and decide if you wish to add it
   to your database.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_UPDATE
@TITLE "Update Floppy"

   This command reads again the contents of the selected Floppy.

   Use this command to update the database when the contents of a Floppy
   changes. What it does is perform a @{"Kill" link DO_KILL} on the Floppy and then reads
   that Floppy again.

   After you answer the requester , you get a chance to edit the new version.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_VIEW
@TITLE "View Floppy"

   Use this command to view the contents of a selected Floppy.

   You'll be presented with the @{"view window" link VIEW_WINDOW}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_EDIT
@TITLE "Edit Floppy"

   Use this command to edit the contents of a selected Floppy.

   The @{"Floppy Contents" link FLOPPY_CONTENTS} window will open to allow for editing.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_KILL
@TITLE "Kill Floppy"

   Kill Floppy completely erases the selected Floppy. You can use multi -
   select to kill several floppies at once.

   You'll be asked to confirm this action.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_FIND
@TITLE "Find Files"

   This is the most important command in FBase as it is used to locate files.

   Invoking this command open the @{"Search window" link SEARCH_WINDOW} where you specify
   what files you're looking for.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_KEYS
@TITLE "Edit Keys"

   Issuing the Keys command open the @{"Keys window" link KEYS_WINDOW} where you
   edit the global @{"Keys" link KEYS}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_RENAME
@TITLE "Rename Record"

   Use this command to Rename a Record (Directory or File).

   To rename a record select it and invoke Rename. A window containing the
   Record name in a string gadget will apear. Change the name and hit RETURN ,
   or close the window to abort change.

   A good use will be to give one descriptive name to a complete directory
   and @{"Delete" link DO_DELETE} the rest of the directory.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_DELETE
@TITLE "Delete Record"

   This command is for Deleting Records.

   To delete a file select it and invoke Delete. You can delete several
   files at once with multi-select.
   To delete a complete directory + sub directories select the directory
   and invoke Delete. You'll be asked to confirm this.
   Choose Yes to delete the directory & all it's contents. Choose Only Below
   to delete the contents of the directory but not the header.

   You cannot delete a complete Floppy. Use @{"Kill Floppy" link DO_KILL} instead.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_REMARK
@TITLE "Record Remark"

   This command opens a window where the Record Remark can be edited. Hitting
   RETURN in the string gadget causes the Remark to change. Cancel the operation
   with the ESC key or by closing the window.

   Any Record can have a remark associated with it. Use these remarks to note
   important info about that file.
   When reading a floppy , the Remark fields is copied from the file's comment
   field. (see AmigaDOS FileNote command).

@ENDNODE

@NODE DO_RKEYS
@TITLE "Record Keys"

   This command opens the @{"Record Keys" link RKEYS_WINDOW} window.
   In that window you set the @{"Keys" link KEYS} associated with the selected Record.

@ENDNODE

@NODE KEYS
@TITLE "Global Keys"

   What are keys?

   Well, FBase allows you to define up to 32 unique attributes for your files.
   Each attribute or key is actually a string (up to 15 chars long) describing
   some feature of the file. Each file can be assigned a combination of these
   keys. When searching for files you can instruct FBase to search for files
   with certain attributes.

   Example:

    Define the following global keys:
     PD
     SHAREWARE
     TEXT
     UTIL
     GAME
     FISHDISK
     LHA
     ARC
     GREAT!

    Then you can assign a file (say FBase.lha) with the following keys:
     PD
     UTIL
     LHA
     GREAT!

    The next step will be to search for all your GREAT! + UTIL , and voila!

@ENDNODE

@NODE WILDCARDS
@Title "Amiga Wildcards"

   This is a short description of amiga wildcards (taken from DOS AutoDocs).

        ?       Matches a single character.
        #       Matches the following expression 0 or more times.
        (ab|cd) Matches any one of the items seperated by '|'.
        ~       Negates the following expression.  It matches all strings
                that do not match the expression (aka ~(foo) matches all
                strings that are not exactly "foo").
        [abc]   Character class: matches any of the characters in the class.
        [~bc]   Character class: matches any of the characters not in the
                class.
        a-z     Character range (only within character classes).
        %       Matches 0 characters always (useful in "(foo|bar|%)").
        *       Synonym for "#?", not available by default in 2.0.  Available
                as an option that can be turned on.

        "Expression" in the above table means either a single character
        (ex: "#?"), or an alternation (ex: "#(ab|cd|ef)"), or a character
        class (ex: "#[a-zA-Z]").

@ENDNODE

